status_message: Knock Every Door—formed in January by a group of Sanders campaign alums and led by his organizing guru Becky Bond—is an oddity among the hundreds of liberal groups that have popped up in the wake of Trump's election. status_message:
ATTENTION FELLOW BERNIE SANDERS SUPPORTERS.

The vast majority of our writers and editors are Bernie supporters, 90% of our 2016 election opinion articles are pro-Bernie, and we give his campaign immense media coverage. We're not hiding the fact that we #FeelTheBern, however we have a responsibility to be better than the DNC and actually allow a debate to take place. 

If our opinion contributors write a pro-Hillary or pro-O'Malley article, or if one of our writers critiques Bernie, it's not because we want to bash him. It's because an honest and open debate on the issues will only make our candidates stronger. 

So please, keep an open mind and an open heart, and don't let Bernie become the left wing version of the GOP Reagan fetish.

Also, join us in knocking on some doors or phonebanking. Waving signs and posting on Facebook is nothing compared to direct voter contact!
Bet the mainstream media won't ever report this.

status_message:
Yesterday, Young Progressive Voices published an article discussing Hillary Clinton's alleged defense of a criminal that has since been pulled due to the large negative feedback we received on it. As a result, we would also like to issue an apology, as well as an explanation.

Soon after the Democratic debate, the network news began misinterpreting or misrepresenting many polls about the winner of the debate, with the majority of them claiming Hillary to the be "clear" winner.

The majority of us here at YPV don't try and hide the fact that the candidate we wish to win the nomination is Bernie Sanders. As a result, the thought process was to publish a piece degrading Hillary and that was what ultimately lead to the publication of the aforementioned article.

While we at YPV are not afraid of publishing/promoting controversial articles (see our pro-O'Malley piece and "Great Games that Actually Suck" series), we do recognize the severe flaws present in the lawyer one and apologize to our fans and readers. Our job is not to promote yellow journalism, but to in fact change the political zeitgeist by advocating for stronger youth participation in politics. Such articles that promote the usual playground politics rhetoric don't help that goal and only alienate our established fans.

We hope you will not take one bad article as an indication that our publishing medium as a whole is flawed. We all make mistakes, and our job is to recognize, fix, and prevent future ones.

In addition to this, as one of our readers commented on yesterday's Hillary post, we do not want Bernie supporters to hate Ms. Clinton. Should she win the nomination, we need all progressives to rally behind her, even if they are disappointed with Sander's lack of being chosen. Because if the Republicans win the White House, we all lose.

As reparations for that article, we have written a new article showcasing the positive aspects of Hillary from the Democratic Debate. We hope you all recognize her greatness! #DemDebate
link_name: 5 Great Things We Learned About Hillary From The Debate

status_message:
Statement from America's Youth Chairman Jacob Daruvala:

Today we received fantastic news that the Supreme Court of the United States has affirmed the constitutional right to marry regardless of gender. We join millions of marriage equality supporters across the United States in celebrating this great victory for civil rights.

It is hard to imagine the enormous impact this ruling will have on LGBT families across the country. Not only will couples be able to commit themselves to one another, but their children will no longer see their LGBT parents' love as something forbidden by the state. The enormous harm and confusion marriage bans have caused will be looked upon in history as a tragedy of the past, another struggle for civil rights that was fought for and won by progressive action and advocacy.

We especially celebrate the message that has been sent to youth in America (many of whom are struggling with their own self-identity), that the government cannot tell you who you can or can't commit your love to. However, youth also cannot take this win for granted. Growing up in a world where the vast majority of your peers believe in equality and your rights have been affirmed by the state can make you forget that this fight was long, hard, sometimes deadly, and that the march for full equality has many more steps ahead.

Today, like so many others, I will celebrate with the one I love and with the ones who support our love. 

Jacob Daruvala

Let's get a discussion going. While movements like Run Bernie Run and Ready for Bernie have been quickly picking up steam, they pale in comparison to the multi-million dollar effort of Ready For Hillary. And with the field almost completely barren and practically nobody jumping at the bit to join, there are few other options besides Hillary.

We can't let a Republican get the almost assured opportunity to appoint 4 Supreme Court Justices, but we're loathe to elect another corporate, hawkish, Democrat. As progressives, what can we do to best push the needle towards real progress and change?
Hillary is in. What are your thoughts?
